VALUES
(42, 23, 5, 43, 2, 11, 11, 'beginning from Galilee', 'Connection of Galilee and Miracles', 'This connection highlights the significance of Galilee in Jesus'' ministry. Both passages emphasize the beginning of Jesus'' influence and miracles in this region, showcasing his role in stirring up the people.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 5, 40, 4, 23, 23, 'teaching throughout all Jewry', 'Teaching and Influence of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' teaching throughout Galilee. Luke highlights the reaction of the people to His influence, while Matthew details His activities in the region.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 5, 19, 22, 12, 13, 'the more fierce', 'Imagery of Aggression and Opposition', 'This connection highlights the fierce opposition faced by Jesus in Luke, paralleling the aggressive imagery of bulls and lions in Psalms. Both passages emphasize the hostility and threats from powerful adversaries surrounding the speaker.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 5, 19, 57, 4, 4, 'stirreth up the people', 'Conflict with Hostile Forces', 'This connection highlights the theme of danger and hostility faced by the faithful. In Luke, the accusation of stirring up the people reflects the fierce opposition, while in Psalms, the imagery of lions and sharp weapons symbolizes the threats against the psalmist.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 5, 40, 4, 12, 16, 'beginning from Galilee to this place', 'Connection of Galilee and Light', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' ministry in Galilee, where he began teaching and bringing light to those in darkness. The reference to ''Galilee'' in both texts highlights its significance in Jesus'' early ministry and fulfillment of prophecy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 6, 42, 13, 1, 1, 'Galilean', 'Connection of Galilee and Pilate', 'This connection highlights Pilate''s involvement with Galileans in both passages. In Luke 23:6, Pilate''s inquiry about a Galilean links to the mention of Galileans in Luke 13:1, where he is implicated in their deaths.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 6, 44, 5, 37, 37, 'whether the man were a Galilean', 'Connection of Galilee References', 'This connection highlights the significance of Galilee in both passages. In Luke, Pilate''s inquiry about Jesus being a Galilean suggests a regional identity, while Acts references Judas of Galilee, indicating a historical figure from the same region who led a movement.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 7, 42, 3, 1, 1, 'Herod’s jurisdiction', 'Connection of Herod''s Jurisdiction', 'This connection highlights the relationship between Herod''s authority in both passages. In Luke 3:1, Herod is identified as tetrarch, while in Luke 23:7, Jesus is sent to him due to jurisdiction.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 7, 42, 13, 31, 31, NULL, 'Herod''s Role in Jesus'' Fate', 'This connection highlights Herod''s involvement in the events surrounding Jesus. In both passages, Herod is mentioned as a figure of authority who poses a threat to Jesus'' life.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 7, 40, 14, 1, 1, 'Herod’s jurisdiction', 'Herod''s Jurisdiction and Fame', 'This connection highlights Herod''s role in the narrative surrounding Jesus. Both passages emphasize Herod''s involvement during significant events related to Jesus'' ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 8, 40, 14, 1, 1, 'desirous to see him', 'Herod''s Interest in Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Herod''s awareness of Jesus'' fame. In Luke, Herod is described as ''desirous to see him,'' while Matthew notes that he ''heard of the fame of Jesus.'' This connection highlights Herod''s curiosity and interest in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 8, 41, 6, 14, 14, 'he hoped to have seen some miracle done by him', 'Herod''s Curiosity About Jesus', 'This connection highlights Herod''s interest in miraculous works. Both passages emphasize Herod''s desire to see Jesus and the association with mighty works.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 8, 42, 9, 7, 9, NULL, 'Herod''s Desire to See Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize Herod''s desire to see Jesus. In Luke 9:9, he expresses this desire after hearing about Jesus'' miracles, which connects to his exceeding gladness in Luke 23:8. This connection highlights Herod''s curiosity and intrigue about Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 8, 12, 5, 11, 11, 'desirous to see him of a long season', 'Desire for Miraculous Healing', 'This connection highlights the desire for miraculous intervention in both passages. Herod''s hope to see a miracle parallels Naaman''s expectation of a specific healing method.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 8, 42, 4, 23, 23, 'he hoped to have seen some miracle', 'Desire for Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of expectation for miracles. In both passages, there is a longing to witness miraculous acts, as seen in Herod''s desire to see Jesus perform a miracle and the proverb referencing healing done in Capernaum.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 8, 44, 8, 19, 19, 'he hoped to have seen some miracle', 'Desire for Miraculous Power', 'This connection highlights the desire for miraculous power in both passages. Herod''s hope to see a miracle from Jesus parallels Simon''s request for the ability to impart the Holy Spirit''s power.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 8, 12, 5, 3, 6, 'he hoped to have seen some miracle', 'Desire for Healing and Miracles', 'This connection highlights the theme of seeking miraculous healing. In both passages, individuals express a strong desire to witness or receive healing from affliction, whether it be Herod''s hope to see a miracle from Jesus or Naaman''s pursuit of healing from leprosy through the prophet.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 9, 40, 27, 14, 14, 'answered him nothing', 'Silence Before Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the silence of Jesus during questioning. This shared theme highlights the profound impact of His non-response on those in authority.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 9, 19, 38, 13, 14, 'answered him nothing', 'Silence in Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize a state of silence in the face of questioning or suffering. In Luke, the silence of Jesus contrasts with the expectation of response, while in Psalms, the speaker describes being mute and unresponsive.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 9, 19, 39, 1, 2, 'he answered him nothing', 'Silence in the Face of Oppression', 'This connection highlights the theme of silence in the face of questioning or wickedness. Both passages emphasize the act of remaining silent, as seen in ''he answered him nothing'' and ''I was dumb with silence.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 9, 23, 53, 7, 7, 'he answered him nothing', 'Silence in Suffering', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of silence in the face of oppression. In Luke, the phrase ''he answered him nothing'' parallels Isaiah''s description of one who ''opened not his mouth'' during affliction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 9, 40, 7, 6, 6, 'answered him nothing', 'Silence and Worthiness', 'This connection highlights the theme of discernment regarding what is valuable. In Luke, the silence of Jesus can be seen as a refusal to engage with those who do not recognize his worth, paralleling Matthew''s warning against giving valuable things to those who cannot appreciate them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 9, 42, 13, 32, 32, 'he answered him nothing', 'Silence and Response to Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of silence in the face of authority. In both passages, Jesus responds to questioning or threats without direct answers, emphasizing his control over the situation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 9, 44, 8, 32, 32, 'but he answered him nothing', 'Silence Before Accusation', 'This connection highlights the theme of silence in the face of accusation. In Luke 23:9, Jesus remains silent when questioned, paralleling the description in Acts 8:32 of being ''dumb before his shearer.''', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 10, 42, 11, 53, 53, 'vehemently', 'Vehement Accusations and Provocations', 'Both passages emphasize the vehement actions of the scribes, highlighting their aggressive stance towards Jesus. In Luke 23:10, they accuse him, while in Luke 11:53, they provoke him, demonstrating a consistent theme of hostility.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 10, 42, 23, 2, 2, 'vehemently accused him', 'Accusation of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the chief priests and scribes in accusing Jesus. In Luke 23:2, they specifically accuse him of perverting the nation, while in Luke 23:10, they stand and vehemently accuse him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 10, 42, 23, 5, 5, 'vehemently accused him', 'Accusations Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the fierce accusations made by the chief priests and scribes against Jesus. In Luke 23:5, they claim he stirs up the people, while in Luke 23:10, they vehemently accuse him, highlighting their hostility.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 10, 42, 23, 14, 15, 'vehemently accused him', 'Accusation and Innocence Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of accusation against Jesus. In both passages, the chief priests and scribes vehemently accuse him, yet Pilate finds no fault in him, emphasizing the contrast between their accusations and the declaration of his innocence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 10, 44, 24, 5, 5, 'vehemently accused him', 'Accusations Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the accusations made against Jesus. In Luke, the chief priests and scribes vehemently accuse him, while in Acts, he is described as a pestilent fellow and a ringleader, indicating ongoing hostility towards him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 11, 41, 15, 16, 20, 'mocked him', 'Mocking of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus by authorities. In Luke, Herod and his men mock him, while in Mark, the soldiers also mock him and dress him in royal attire.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
